.docname {Broadcast Workflow}
.docauthor {BakingRL}
.include {docs}
.doclang {en}

The first-party broadcast stack is composed from independent Runtime API 2.3
plugins. BakingRL supplies the runtime, windows, telemetry, permissions, and
installation flow; product behavior remains in plugins.

## Dependency Direction

```txt
Extended Statistics -> Layout Studio -> Broadcast Visuals
                               |
                               +-> OBS Gateway
```

PlayerStreak and Deja Vu add optional services and visuals through the same
Layout Studio extension point.

## Extended Statistics

`bakingrl.stats-extended` owns reusable telemetry aggregation. It persists
series, match, player, team, and cage statistics and exposes stable services to
other plugins. Its dashboard inspects those values.

It does not own layout documents, overlay windows, visual composition, or OBS
networking.

## Layout Studio

`bakingrl.layout-studio` owns saved layout documents and the layout editor. A
document contains canvas geometry, layers, native text/image/shape items, and
references to plugin-contributed visuals.

Layout Studio exposes `bakingrl.layout-studio/visual` so visual packs can join
the catalogue without changing the host or editor. Its service provides the
same active document to local overlay rendering and OBS Gateway.

Layout Studio decides what is placed, where it is placed, and which layout is
active. It does not define the complete first-party visual catalogue and does
not serve HTTP routes to OBS.

## Broadcast Visuals

`bakingrl.broadcast-visuals` contributes the first-party responsive renderers:
scoreboards, player panels, goal and victory scenes, team events, cage maps,
and statistics views. Each contribution targets the Layout Studio visual
extension point and declares remote rendering compatibility.

Its control webview manages broadcast state. It does not own saved layouts or
the layout editor, and it is not the OBS web server.

## Local Overlay

The local game overlay is a host-opened plugin surface. The host owns window
lifecycle, bounds, transparency, always-on-top, click-through, and screen
selection. Layout Studio and visual plugins own the rendered content.

The visual must fill the rectangle assigned by the layout. Resizing the surface
or item should reflow the visual rather than preserving an unrelated fixed
scale.

## OBS Gateway

`bakingrl.obs-gateway` is the bridge to OBS Studio. Its supervised native
sidecar exposes configurable local HTTP browser-source URLs, health and
snapshot APIs, Server-Sent Events, and WebSocket events.

The gateway reads active Layout Studio documents through the
`bakingrl.layout-studio/layoutStudio` service and refreshes on layout-change
events. It renders the same native items and remote-compatible visual modules.
It does not synthesize layouts from installed resources.

In short:

- Layout Studio edits and stores compositions;
- Broadcast Visuals supplies renderable blocks;
- the local overlay displays a composition above the game;
- OBS Gateway publishes that composition over HTTP for OBS browser sources;
- OBS Studio consumes the URL and remains an external application.
